  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How realistic is asking for a 175k base salary, 20% bonus, and 100K in stock per year at a very successful software corporation in the Bay Area (Google), for a computer science PhD (from a top 5 school) for a research-oriented role?",
  "response": "Asking for a base salary of $175,000, a 20% bonus, and $100,000 in stock per year at a major tech company like Google is within the realm of possibility, especially for a candidate with a Ph.D. in Computer Science from a top-tier institution targeting a research-oriented role. Here are several factors to consider:\n\n1. **Market Trends**: Compensation packages in the tech industry, especially in the Bay Area, have seen significant increases over the years. High demand for talent, particularly for roles that require advanced degrees and specialized skills, has contributed to this trend.\n\n2. **Company Standards**: Google is known for offering competitive compensation to attract top talent. They often provide substantial equity components, particularly for highly skilled positions.\n\n3. **Role Expectations**: Research-oriented roles, especially in fields like AI, machine learning, and data science, may command higher salaries due to the scarcity of qualified candidates and the advanced expertise required.\n\n4. **Experience and Skills**: Your negotiation position will also depend on your relevant experience, publications, and specific skills that align with the role. The more specialized and relevant your qualifications are, the stronger your case for a higher salary.\n\n5. **Compensation Structure**: Understand that total compensation at tech companies often includes bonuses and stock options, especially notable in companies like Google. A 20% bonus and substantial stock options can significantly enhance the overall package.\n\n6. **Networking and Industry Comparisons**: It can be helpful to look at compensation data from websites like Glassdoor, Levels.fyi, or blind.com to see what others in similar roles and companies are earning. This can provide a benchmark for your negotiations.\n\nUltimately, it's vital to present a strong case based on your qualifications and market data when discussing salary. If you feel that your skills and background warrant the package you are asking for, it is reasonable to put that offer on the table. Just be prepared for negotiations, as companies may counter with lower offers, and understanding the full compensation package will help you assess the offer comprehensively.",
